04086nam a22006255i 9780292763777DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211999txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927637777 a10.7560/7282192doi  a(DE-B1597)586487  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aLIT0041002bisacsh00aMachado de Assis :bReflections on a Brazilian Master Writer /ced. by Richard Graham. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1999  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Dom Casmurro: Realism and Intentionalism Revisited -- t2. Dom Casmurro: Simulacrum and Allegory -- t3. Dependents Play Chess: Political Dialogues in Machado de Assis -- t4. Machado in English -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJoaquim Maria Machado de Assis (1839-1908) never left Brazil and rarely traveled outside his native city of Rio de Janeiro, yet he is widely acknowledged by those who have read him as one of the major authors of the nineteenth century. His works are full of subtle irony, relentless psychological insights, and brilliant literary innovations. Yet, because he wrote in Portuguese, a language outside the mainstream of Western culture, those with access to his writings are relatively few. This book is designed not only to call new attention to this master but also to raise questions about the nature of literature itself and current alternative views on how it can be approached. Four essays address the question of Machado's "realism" in the five masterpiece novels of his maturity, especially Dom Casmurro. The noted contributors include John Gledson (University of Liverpool), João Adolfo Hansen (Universidade de São Paulo), Sidney Chalhoub (Universidade de Campinas), and Daphne Patai (University of Massachusetts at Amherst). Dain Borges of the University of California at San Diego says, "[This is the] only collection explicitly debating the question that polarizes contemporary Brazilian criticism of Machado de Assis: was he a sophisticated late realist, or was he a pioneering anti-realist, even a postmodernist? The [essayists] marshal their evidence and argument with virtuosity and arrive at sharply opposing conclusions."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh1 aChalhoub, Sidney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGledson, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraham, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHansen, João Adolfo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatai, Daphne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292763777423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292763777/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK